    "body": "### Feature already in Vim?\n\nNo\n\n### Feature description\n\nThis is sort of related to #1419 but it is not the same thing: elastic tabstops, as I understand it, rely on different text being written in the source file (to use tabs, which will then be rendered more creatively).\r\n\r\nWhat I want to do is render two spaces in the text at the start of lines as a `\\t` (which I can then change the width of with ts=), or some other number of spaces as I struggle a *lot* with reading 2-space-indented codebases due to a disability, and there is not much that can be done to avoid reading these, so I want my editor to help me with this by allowing me to visually indent them at a larger size without changing the text content of the file.\r\n\r\nThis functionality exists in VSCode as an extension that does some funny CSS to render the spaces scaled in width (their approach would not work for nvim of course):\r\nhttps://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=kylepaulsen.stretchy-spaces\r\n\r\nCurrently, doing something like `:exe \"syn match Normal '    ' contained conceal cchar=\\t\"` does not work as it will throw an \"E844: invalid cchar value\". I maintain an indent guides plugin that can match leading indents for highlighting purposes, so making this mechanism work with concealing as tabs or multiple characters would achieve the stated goal, I believe.",
